es%2F98e196b0-ca1d-4662-80c6-e48d8f747be2_1477x800.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">来源： <a href="https://www.csis.org/analysis/green-industrial-policy-holistic-approach">CSIS</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>因此，如果您是美国人，那么您昨天就不会购买中国电动汽车，现在您也不会明天购买。什么都不会改变。</p><p>但这并不意味着这些关税具有表演性。他们是<em>预防性</em>。过去，我们看到了中国突然在美国或其他国家泛滥的某个出口产品的例子，例如<a href="https://twitter.com/Brad_Setser/status/1790236572731781130">挖掘机</a>。拜登的关税将确保电动汽车不会发生这种情况。</p><p>那好还是坏？关税会使美国人的生活更昂贵吗？拜登的举动会促进美国汽车行业吗？它会减慢绿色过渡吗？这对美国贸易政策意味着什么？</p><p>我将尝试回答这些问题。</p><h4>中国电动汽车的关税是否会使美国人的生活更昂贵？</h4><p>这个问题的简短答案是“否”，原因只是上面的图表。美国人没有购买任何中国电动汽车，因此中国电动汽车的价格不仅仅是使美国人为任何东西付出更多。</p><p>现在，关税<em>可能</em>是为了防止未来的廉价Ev Bonanza到达美国的海岸。如果拜登什么也没做，中国可能会以便宜的高品质高品质电动汽车淹没美国。然后，一群因高利率和食品杂货价格而感到压力的美国人可能可以通过购买廉价的高质量中国制造的电动汽车来获得一些缓解。</p><p>中国电动汽车<em>非常</em>好。中国一直在努力制造出良好的内燃机，但向电动汽车的转变使他们完全超越了冰车。由于中国在电池行业中占主导地位，因此掌握电动汽车非常容易。凯文·威廉姆斯（Kevin Williams）有<a href="https://insideevs.com/features/719015/china-is-ahead-of-west/">一篇关于中国电动汽车高质量的文章</a>，尽管它包含相当一部分的手挥舞“我们煮过的”等等，但您还是应该阅读的。威廉姆斯的结论是：</p><blockquote><p>如果美国和欧洲如愿以偿——对中国进口进行打击——那么人们感觉不会生产出更好的汽车。感觉这会让这些市场的买家锁定那些性能不佳的汽车。这是赤裸裸的保护主义，因为在内心深处，所有西方汽车高管和一些鹰派的中国专家都明白，中国的电动汽车和插电式混合动力车型比欧洲、其他亚洲和美国品牌的产品更引人注目。</p></blockquote><p>这是对的。而且有理由担心，如果没有中国进口的竞争压力，通用汽车和福特等人（甚至是特斯拉）的竞争压力将少得多地复制创新的中文功能（例如基于屏幕的控件）的理由。美国消费者最终可能会选择较低的车辆选择。</p><p>但是我认为这不会发生，这是出于一个简单的原因：<em>中国汽车公司不必在中国制造汽车</em>。</p><p>关税是根据良好进行最终组装的位置提出的。因此，如果Byd或其他中国汽车制造商将其工厂放到美国，墨西哥，加拿大或中国以外的任何地方 - 他们仍然可以将电动汽车出售给美国而不会受到Biden的新关税的打击。这<a href="https://www.wsj.com/business/autos/chinese-ev-maker-byd-exploring-mexico-factory-as-entry-to-u-s-market-411360fa">已经在进行中</a>：</p><blockquote><p>中国汽车制造商比德（Byd）将目光投向了墨西哥，因为它寻求<a href="https://www.wsj.com/business/autos/chinas-ev-champion-byd-will-take-on-the-world-in-2024-9da4cfde?mod=article_inline">全球扩张</a>向北美的追求变化……在墨西哥为美国建造汽车将允许汽车制造商避免，如果他们直接从中国派出中国，他们将征收高额进口关税……近年来，至少有十二个中国电动汽车组件供应商宣布了新的工厂或增加了他们在墨西哥的现有投资[。]</p></blockquote><p>墨西哥的中国汽车工厂将能够利用中国的供应链（尤其是电池），降低其成本。他们将通过凯文·威廉姆斯（Kevin Williams）非常喜欢的那些大屏幕界面进行创新的中国设计。他们将结合中国工厂发现的任何集会创新，进一步推动成本。</p><p>因此，美国人仍然能够获得“中国”电动汽车，而不是来自中国工厂。没关系。墨西哥需要工作和收入，美国消费者可以使用一些廉价的未来派汽车，美国汽车公司可以使用竞争对手。</p><p>一个公开的问题是，中国政府将决定在墨西哥的中国拥有的工厂进行补贴。从理论上讲，中国可以部署它用于补贴国内生产的所有相同政策工具 - 税收抵免，廉价贷款，直接付款等，以帮助中国公司从墨西哥工厂抽出便宜的汽车。这是否完全是另一个问题 - 中国政府可能希望在该国保持制造业工作，从而对FDI进行补贴。所以我们拭目以待。</p><p>但是，即使没有补贴，中国公司确实确实制造了便宜的好电动汽车，美国人仍然能够在新的关税制度下掌握它们。</p><p>当然，如果我们还对在墨西哥和其他第三国制造的电动汽车征收关税，这会变得更加困难。实际上，特朗普<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-05-12/biden-s-china-tariffs-salvo-to-range-from-doubling-to-quadruple?sref=R8NfLgwS">已经在威胁到这一点</a>：</p><blockquote><p> [特朗普]警告说，中国公司将尝试在墨西哥制造汽车，然后根据美国 - 墨西哥 - 加拿大协议将其运送到美国，避免关税，特朗普同意该协议作为总统。特朗普说，他将在墨西哥对中国制造的汽车征收200％的关税。</p></blockquote><p>如果将关税扩大到包括墨西哥等第三国，那么美国消费者确实<em>可以</em>被锁定在尖端电动汽车的市场上。到那时，中国汽车公司避免关税的唯一途径就是在美国制造汽车。日本品牌<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/whos-afraid-of-east-asian-management">取得了成功</a>。但是中国公司可能<a href="https://finance.yahoo.com/news/tesla-rival-byd-not-planning-to-come-to-the-us-exec-says-212306507.html?guccounter=1&amp;guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&amp;guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAFivsL7qUpNWPP-cfSUt0j5PQUm5ibp_ujyWm-kg_RkaeAezjzATUNk5iISI6OHDIinXzOht6YxPy0KUwSFUs43kSdE2icPp73w0HmjLGO0NXM4BpSHDCG1ljf2gKLHRF81dm56VNwjE2MjyQRqPMtfQyQykGiOIu4q_H_D_emgM">不愿这样做</a>，或者他们的政府可能阻止他们这样做。所以我们拭目以待。</p><h4>关税对美国汽车行业意味着什么？</h4><p>拜登的关税将为我们的汽车公司和福特等汽车公司提供暂时的缓刑。但是，除非拜登（或未来的特朗普总统）也对墨西哥的电动汽车征收关税，否则喘息的时间将是短暂的，因为通用汽车和福特仍将面临来自中国汽车制造商在国内市场的品牌竞争。</p><p>这场比赛不仅打击了通用汽车和福特的新生电动汽车业务 - 它将打击他们的整个业务。冰车和电动汽车正处于直接竞争。从长远来看，有几种有利于电动汽车的结构性因素。这些包括：</p><ol><li><p>政府为加速绿色过渡的努力</p></li><li><p>冰技术基本上停滞不前，电池技术正在飞跃和界限进步</p></li><li><p>由于缩放效果，每年电池成本都会下降这一事实（主要来自中国）</p></li><li><p>家庭充电</p></li></ol><p>去年，我写了一篇文章，认为电动汽车注定要取代冰车，而变化将很快发生： </p><div class="digest-post-embed" data-attrs="{&quot;nodeId&quot;:&quot;adb2e3b8-f401-46dd-84b3-d3cf2bc49805&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;It&#8217;s time for another techno-optimist post! Instead of an as-yet-unproven technology like green hydrogen or battery-powered appliances, today&#8217;s post is about a technology that&#8217;s already taking over the world: battery electric vehicles, commonly known as EVs.&quot;,&quot;size&quot;:&quot;sm&quot;,&quot;isEditorNode&quot;:true,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;All the arguments against EVs are wrong&quot;,&quot;publishedBylines&quot;:[{&quot;id&quot;:8243895,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Noah Smith&quot;,&quot;bio&quot;:&quot;Econ blogger&quot;,&quot;photo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/89fd964a-586f-461a-9f5a-ea4587d45728_397x441.png&quot;,&quot;is_guest&quot;:false,&quot;bestseller_tier&quot;:10000}],&quot;post_date&quot;:&quot;2023-05-14T07:05:30.107Z&quot;,&quot;cover_image&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ef19f80-7aea-45fd-be51-18fa1416f9f9_1166x773.jpeg&quot;,&quot;cover_image_alt&quot;:null,&quot;canonical_url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/all-the-arguments-against-evs-are&quot;,&quot;section_name&quot;:null,&quot;id&quot;:121266134,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;newsletter&quot;,&quot;reaction_count&quot;:449,&quot;comment_count&quot;:393,&quot;publication_name&quot;:&quot;Noahpinion&quot;,&quot;publication_logo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F04281755-2cd6-42e5-a496-e69153abebb2_281x281.png&quot;,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true}"></div><p>与电动汽车不同，冰车必须经常填充，电动汽车在人们的车库里过夜，因此只需要长途旅行。因此，冰车需要密集的加油站网络才能可行。随着电动汽车开始接管市场，冰车变得稀少，我们现有的许多加油站将倒闭。这将使拥有内燃机汽车变得不那么方便，从而加速向电动汽车的转变。冲洗并重复。一旦此过程开始，汽油动力的汽车将很快成为利基产品，而电动汽车将成为大多数人驾驶的汽车。</p><p>现在，这种情况还没有发生。 The market for EVs in the US is still increasing, but not as fast as many had expected, and as a result US automakers are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/business/autos/general-motors-gm-q3-earnings-report-2023-5064f4c2">scaling back their EV plans</a> .</p><p> But most Americans — except for a hard core of conservatives who have turned green technology into a culture war — expect to get an EV in the not-too-distant future: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg" width="800" height="418" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:418,&quot;width&quot;:800,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:65632,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://www.sustainabilitybynumbers.com/p/american-attitudes-ev?utm_source=post-email-title&amp;publication_id=1199196&amp;post_id=143703245&amp;utm_campaign=email-post-title&amp;isFreemail=true&amp;r=4wp13&amp;triedRedirect=true&amp;utm_medium=email">Hannah Ritchie</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> If GM and Ford scale back their offerings, and if Tesla focuses on robotaxis instead of new better EVs, then there&#39;s a high likelihood that the EV revolution in America will be carried out by Chinese companies building cars in Mexico. Tariffs won&#39;t stop that, unless A) we levy similar tariffs on Mexico and any other country, and B) Chinese car companies refuse to build factories in the US</p><p> And there&#39;s something else that <em>no</em> US tariff can stop: American car companies getting outcompeted in export markets.</p><p> Ford makes the bulk of its money <a href="https://stockdividendscreener.com/auto-manufacturers/ford-global-vehicle-sales-and-market-share/">from North America</a> , but GM makes <a href="https://stockdividendscreener.com/auto-manufacturers/general-motors-vehicle-sales-and-market-share/">as much or more revenue in Asia</a> , as does <a href="https://www.statista.com/statistics/314759/revenue-of-tesla-by-region/">Tesla</a> . US tariffs obviously do not apply to Chinese EVs being sold to Vietnam, or Japan, or Australia, or anywhere else except the US So they will do absolutely nothing to help US automakers compete in key foreign markets. Many of those other countries are unlikely to put up giant Biden-style tariffs on Chinese EVs, so GM and Ford and Tesla will be facing BYD and the other Chinese automakers on a more-or-less level playing field overseas (except in China itself, where the government will tip the scales in favor of its own domestic brands).</p><p> Chinese competition could thus push American and other car companies out of world markets. That would exacerbate the existing trend: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg" width="836" height="471" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:471,&quot;width&quot;:836,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:164754,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://stockdividendscreener.com/auto-manufacturers/general-motors-vehicle-sales-and-market-share/">StockDividendScreener.com</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> US car companies — like European, Japanese, and Korean car companies — are thus in grave danger, tariffs or no. The EV transition is happening, and China is the best at EVs. Unless they can raise their game, they are, in the words of Kevin Williams, “cooked”.</p><h4>关税会减缓绿色转型吗？</h4><p> A lot of people are worried that tariffs like these will slow down the transition to a low-carbon future powered by solar power and batteries. For example, <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2024-03-17/trade-wars-bans-on-evs-and-solar-panels-are-not-the-answer?sref=R8NfLgwS">David Fickling writes</a> :</p><blockquote><p>中国在清洁技术方面日益扩大的领先地位，加上其巨大的贸易顺差……与发达国家在脱碳方面步履蹒跚的努力相结合，产生了有毒的混合物……如果电动汽车等绿色技术……被贴上外国和威胁的标签，并发现自己被排除在外…… tariff policies, then drastically falling costs aren&#39;t going to be enough to get it into the hands of consumers…An acceleration in trade wars will only slow our path to zero [carbon].</p></blockquote><p> He&#39;s right to worry. Transportation is responsible for <a href="https://www.epa.gov/ghgemissions/sources-greenhouse-gas-emissions">almost 30% of US carbon emissions</a> , or about 4% of the global total. If the US failed to switch to EVs, it could hamper decarbonization efforts by a small but noticeable amount.</p><p> Now, as I said before, if tariffs are only placed on EVs made in China, there&#39;s not much to worry about here. Americans will still switch to EVs, they&#39;ll just buy their Chinese-brand EVs from factories in Mexico. The green transition will continue apace.</p><p> If the US places tariffs on <em>all</em> foreign EVs, though, we could be in trouble. A refusal of GM and Ford to bet big on the EV transition (and Tesla&#39;s pivot to robotaxis) would then be able to keep America as a gas-guzzling nation, clinging to our outmoded comfort cars, orphaned from global technology and locked out of the high-tech future.</p><p> And if Republicans turn EVs into a culture war the way they&#39;ve done with <a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/florida-alabama-lab-grown-mean-ban-2024/">lab-grown meat</a> , they could enact restrictive state-level policies that would slow the transition even further.</p><p> So I am worried about the green transition in the US, though that worry depends very strongly on whether the US extends its tariffs to Mexican-made EVs.</p><h4> What does this mean for trade policy going forward?</h4><p> The most important thing about these tariffs is probably the message they send. Protectionism is now the consensus economic policy of both major political parties in the United States. Biden has extended the Trump tariffs on China and levied the new EV tariffs; Trump is <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-05-12/biden-s-china-tariffs-salvo-to-range-from-doubling-to-quadruple?sref=R8NfLgwS">trying to one-up Biden</a> by promising to raise the 100% tariffs to 200%, extend them to Mexico, and slap an additional 60% tariff on all Chinese-made goods. There is currently no major party or presidential candidate that you can vote for in America that is even remotely interested in free trade.</p><p> But that still leaves lots of questions. Most importantly, there&#39;s the question of what, exactly, protectionism is trying to <em>protect</em> . I see four main potential purposes of tariffs:</p><ol><li><p> Protecting auto industry jobs and/or corporate profits</p></li><li><p>减少对华贸易失衡</p></li><li><p>Eliminating security risks from Chinese hacking</p></li><li><p> Protecting domestic defense manufacturing capacity</p></li></ol><p> The first of these is probably foremost in the minds of many progressives, and possibly Trump as well. On the plus side, if Chinese car companies could be persuaded to put their factories in the US like Japanese car companies did, labor-protectionists would be happy. GM and Ford would still be mad, and they&#39;d probably have some supporters in Congress, but the prospect of a whole bunch of good American manufacturing jobs in BYD or Geely factories would probably win out.</p><p> The second of these — reducing trade imbalances — is what everyone talks about. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/world/china/china-shock-2-0-sparks-global-backlash-against-flood-of-cheap-goods-d394238b">Articles about the Second China Shock</a> usually mention things like Chinese underconsumption, overcapacity, and trade imbalances. The Rhodium Group has a report called “ <a href="https://rhg.com/research/overcapacity-at-the-gate/">Overcapacity at the Gates</a> ” that sums up the viewpoint well. The two most well-known commentators on this issue — or at least, the two I read the most — are <a href="https://twitter.com/Brad_Setser">Brad Setser</a> and <a href="https://twitter.com/michaelxpettis">Michael Pettis</a> , so if you want to learn more about this idea, check them out.</p><p> It&#39;s not clear whether trade imbalances by themselves are a legitimate concern, or whether they&#39;re a catch-all proxy for concerns about jobs and other issues. It&#39;s also not clear whether tariffs can restore trade balance — it&#39;s possible that the expensive dollar is to blame, and that only an abdication of the dollar&#39;s role as the global reserve currency can fix things. More on that in a post coming soon. But for right now, what&#39;s clear is that many people are upset about trade imbalances, and tariffs are one available policy for trying to address those imbalances.</p><p> The third issue — security risks from Chinese-made goods — is something I&#39;m not really qualified to assess. The fear is that if China&#39;s security services put backdoors in Chinese-made products, they could use those built-in vulnerabilities <a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/biden-administration-will-investigate-national-security-risks-posed-ch-rcna141099">to cause havoc in the US</a> in the event of a war:</p><blockquote><p>美国商务部长吉娜·雷蒙多表示，联网汽车“就像车轮上的智能手机”，构成严重的国家安全风险。</p><p> “这些车辆已连接到互联网。 They collect huge amounts of sensitive data on the drivers — personal information, biometric information, where the car goes,&#39;&#39; she told reporters late Wednesday…</p><p>她和其他官员表示，数据收集并不是唯一的问题。联网车辆也可能被不良行为者远程启用或操纵。</p><p> “Imagine if there were thousands or hundreds of thousands of Chinese-connected vehicles on American roads that could be immediately and simultaneously disabled by somebody in Beijing,&#39;&#39; Raimondo said. “So it&#39;s scary to contemplate the cyber risks, espionage risks that these pose.&#39;&#39;</p></blockquote><p> Given how a single wayward cargo ship just <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Scott_Key_Bridge_collapse">took out a major bridge</a> in Baltimore that will take years to repair, it&#39;s pretty terrifying to think about how much destruction China could wreak if it controlled all of our cars.</p><p> I will say, though, that it seems like the danger here is entirely from Chinese-made <em>computer chips</em> .使用中国计算机芯片制造的通用汽车或福特汽车与使用相同芯片制造的比亚迪汽车存在相同的漏洞。 So if you&#39;re worried about cybersecurity, it seems to me that the one and only thing you need to keep out of the US are Chinese-made semiconductors.</p><p>无论如何，这给我们带来了最后一个问题：国防制造能力。在战争时期，民用工厂通常会被重新调整用途来制造战争物资——例如，当福特在第二次世界大战期间<a href="https://www.assemblymag.com/articles/94614-how-fords-willow-run-assembly-plant-helped-win-world-war-ii">生产大量</a>B-24 轰炸机时。我们有一项名为《国防生产法》的法律，允许政府order US companies to switch their production lines to make military equipment or other goods critical to national security (for example, we used the DPA to make companies build ventilators during Covid).</p><p> But the DPA is useless if you <em>don&#39;t have the factories</em> to repurpose. If US heavy manufacturing withers and dies in the face of Chinese competition, the US won&#39;t be able to add much to its defense production capacity in a war. That could lead to a swift and devastating US defeat at the hands of China.</p><p> My guess is that China knows this very well, and that this is one reason it has been so generous with subsidies and so gung-ho about ramping up manufacturing exports.是的，他们当然想要就业和增长，但通过出口补贴强制西方去工业化的诱人潜力无疑已经在每一位中国领导人的脑海中闪过了。</p><p> So in order to have domestic manufacturing available for military repurposing, it&#39;s probably necessary to erect trade barriers to protect against massively subsidized Chinese import surges. This consideration has nothing to do with American jobs or profits or trade deficits — it&#39;s just a cold, hard military reality. Opponents of protectionism — the Cato Institute, the writers at <a href="https://www.economist.com/briefing/2024/05/09/the-worlds-economic-order-is-breaking-down">The Economist</a> , and so on — seem to have no alternative answer here.</p><p>换句话说，关税上涨有多种相互交叉的原因，其中大多数都具有两党的吸引力。 Biden&#39;s big tariffs on Chinese EVs are likely only the start of a major shift in America&#39;s trade policy. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-big-tariffs-are-here?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-big-tariffs-are-here?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><p></p>; 
How I would regulate AIFocus on the choke points in the process by which AI could do harm.https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/how-i-would-regulate-ai https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/how-i-would-regulate-aiNoah Smith Mon, 13 May 2024 07:48:22 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg" width="680" height="680" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1024,&quot;width&quot;:1024,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:680,&quot;bytes&quot;:62463,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption"> Art by GPT-4</figcaption></figure></div><p> I thought I&#39;d take a break from writing about weighty matters like trade wars and presidential elections, and talk about something more whimsical and lighthearted — how to keep quasi-sentient computers from taking all our jobs and then hunting us to extinction with swarms of autonomous drones!</p><p> Well, OK, I don&#39;t think we&#39;re going to be <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/llms-are-not-going-to-destroy-the">facing off with Skynet</a> anytime soon. But generative AI is undeniably a very powerful new technology, and the list of powerful new technologies that the human race hasn&#39;t used for destructive purposes is very short indeed. So it probably makes sense to start thinking about how to use regulation to decrease the likelihood that AI will be used to cause catastrophes.</p><p> That&#39;s a lot easier said than done, however. It&#39;s very hard to predict what kind of regulation would make a technology safer <em>before</em> the harms materialize, and it&#39;s very easy to create regulation that slows down technological progress.因此，<em>从先验来看</em>，人工智能监管的一个相当可能的结果是人工智能进展放缓，但人工智能最终仍会以监管机构从未预料到的方式造成损害。</p><p>意识到这一基本困难后，拜登政府明智地采取了温和的态度——至少在美国。有人猜测， <a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/10/30/fact-sheet-president-biden-issues-executive-order-on-safe-secure-and-trustworthy-artificial-intelligence/">拜登去年 10 月发布的人工智能行政命令</a>将重点限制人工智能能力。但相反，该命令针对存在风险的主要保护只是要求对基础模型（如 ChatGPT 和 Gemini）进行安全测试。它还制定了一些条款来防范人工智能带来的不存在的风险——工作岗位流失、深度造假、隐私侵犯等等。</p><p>然而，目前正在进行的其他尝试将走得更远。加州立法者正在提出一系列<a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1axh0K__Wx6Sy2Gi9atYNT8l0du0w5AuffNYkrVszJSU/edit#gid=644486299">州级人工智能安全法案</a>。其中之一是州参议员 Scott Wiener 的<a href="https://sd11.senate.ca.gov/news/20240208-senator-wiener-introduces-legislation-ensure-safe-development-large-scale-artificial">SB 1047</a> ，它将对构建基础模型的公司提出<a href="https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billNavClient.xhtml?bill_id=202320240SB1047">一系列安全要求</a>。如果发现这些模型造成重大破坏，该法案将要求公司承担部分费用。</p><p>我不是人工智能技术方面的专家，但我想知道这样的规定是否真的可以按照书面规定执行。 SB 1047 要求人工智能公司在模型接受数据训练<em>之前</em>了解其模型可以做和不能做的各种事情。据我所知，这是不可能的；在训练之前，你并不真正知道模型可以做什么。事实上，即使像 ChatGPT 这样的模型经过训练，似乎也不可能真正知道它可以用来做什么危险的事情。有人认为我们现在知道 GPT-4 是否真的有能力在正确的恶棍手中造成灾难性伤害吗？我不这么认为。而 GPT-4 已经面世一年多了；当我们谈论<em>新</em>模型时，我们的知识就更少了。</p><p>因此，我认为像 SB 1047 这样要求人工智能公司对其模型做出各种安全声明的法案，大部分会导致公司做出完全安全的 BS 声明，而没有人能够以某种方式验证这一点。</p><p>我不认为这样的监管会大大减缓人工智能创新，但我也不认为他们会采取很多措施来限制人工智能的实际风险——主要是因为人工智能公司已经在努力限制这些风险。风险自行承担。事实上，我不确定是否<em>有什么</em>可以消除这些风险，因为生成式人工智能是一种黑匣子，而且很难知道它的能力。但我确实有一些关于如何有效监管人工智能的想法，同时又不会给公司带来繁文缛节的垃圾邮件。</p><h4>储备资源供人类使用</h4><p>我将讨论一些关于如何减轻人工智能带来的生存风险的想法——“天网”场景以及类似的事情。但首先我想谈谈什么样的监管可以限制<em>经济</em>风险。很多人都害怕人工智能取代人们的工作，许多人担心我们的物种甚至可能像马一样在经济上被淘汰。但我认为有一个简单的规定可以防止这种结果。</p><p><a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/how-i-would-regulate-ai">阅读更多</a></p>; 
The death (again) of the internet as we know itA few big changes are making the online world a more boring place to hang out. https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-death-again-of-the-internet-as https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-death-again-of-the-internet-asNoah Smith Sat, 11 May 2024 23:43:35 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg" width="710" height="710" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1024,&quot;width&quot;:1024,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:710,&quot;bytes&quot;:68662,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption"> GPT-4 的艺术作品。提示：“互联网之死”</figcaption></figure></div><p>我们所知道的互联网已经消亡过一次了。 2010 年代，智能手机和大众社交媒体（Twitter/Facebook/Instagram）的兴起引发了互联网资深人士所说的整个互联网的<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eternal_September">“永恒九月</a>事件”。 “永恒的九月”是一个古老的俚语，指的是一群普通人涌入以前舒适的精品在线空间。当普通人拥有一台高速袖珍电脑，将他们 24/7 与社交媒体世界连接起来时，互联网就不再是怪人和业余爱好者的领域，而是成为我们整个社会的城镇广场。</p><p>在我看来，这并不是一个很大的改变。人类并没有进化到所有人都在同一个房间里。早期的互联网是一个非常特殊的时代，当时网络世界主要作为那些不太融入线下世界的人的临时逃避或释放阀；大众社交媒体<a href="https://bfi.uchicago.edu/insight/research-summary/when-product-markets-become-collective-traps-the-case-of-social-media/">将互联网变成了一个集体陷阱</a>，一个你<em>必须</em>去的地方，而不是一个你可以逃走的地方。如果你看一下美国青少年的幸福感图表，你会发现从 90 年代中期到 2000 年代，情况有所好转，然后又急剧恶化： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdd6e1312-42b2-444b-b036-0c952ae2ebbd_990x495.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdd6e1312-42b2-444b-b036-0c952ae2ebbd_990x495.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdd6e1312-42b2-444b-b036-0c952ae2ebbd_990x495.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdd6e1312-42b2-444b-b036-0c952ae2ebbd_990x495.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdd6e1312-42b2-444b-b036-0c952ae2ebbd_990x495.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdd6e1312-42b2-444b-b036-0c952ae2ebbd_990x495.jpeg" width="990" height="495" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/dd6e1312-42b2-444b-b036-0c952ae2ebbd_990x495.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;: